1
00:00:19,762 --> 00:00:22,230
{i1}[Clattering Sound]{}

2
00:00:23,666 --> 00:00:25,930
{i1}I'm talkin' about friendship.{}

3
00:00:26,002 --> 00:00:28,664
{i1}I'm talkin' about character.{}

4
00:00:28,738 --> 00:00:32,738
{i1}I'm talkin' about--
Hell, Leo, I ain't embarrassed
to use the word.{}

5
00:00:33,243 --> 00:00:36,406
I'm talkin' about ethics.

6
00:00:36,479 --> 00:00:38,538
You know I'm a sportin' man.

7
00:00:38,615 --> 00:00:41,049
I like to lay the occasional bet.

8
00:00:41,117 --> 00:00:43,677
But I ain't {i1}that{} sportin'.

9
00:00:43,753 --> 00:00:46,654
When I fix a fight--
Say I pay a three to one favorite...

10
00:00:46,723 --> 00:00:48,748
to throw a goddamned fight.

11
00:00:48,825 --> 00:00:52,825
I figure I got the right
to expect that fight
to go off at three to one.

12
00:00:53,029 --> 00:00:56,760
But every time I lay in bed
with this son of a bitch
Bernie Bernbaum,

13
00:00:56,833 --> 00:01:00,132
before I know it,
the odds is even up.

14
00:01:00,203 --> 00:01:02,763
Or worse, I'm bettin'
on the short money.

15
00:01:02,839 --> 00:01:05,103
The sheeny knows
I like sure things.

16
00:01:05,174 --> 00:01:08,632
He's sellin' the information
I fixed the fight.

17
00:01:08,711 --> 00:01:11,077
Out of town money
comes pouring in.

18
00:01:11,147 --> 00:01:13,377
The odds go straight to hell.

19
00:01:13,449 --> 00:01:16,816
I don't know who
he's sellin' to-- maybe
the Los Angeles combine.

20
00:01:16,886 --> 00:01:18,820
{i1}I don't know. The point is,{}

21
00:01:18,888 --> 00:01:22,888
{i1}Bernie ain't satisfied
with the honest dollar
he can make off the vig.{}

22
00:01:23,126 --> 00:01:26,357
He ain't satisfied with
the business I do on his book.

23
00:01:26,429 --> 00:01:29,330
He is sellin' tips on how I bet.

24
00:01:29,399 --> 00:01:32,562
And that means part
of the payoff that should
be riding on my hip...

25
00:01:32,635 --> 00:01:34,796
is riding on someone else's.

26
00:01:34,871 --> 00:01:37,396
So, back we go
to these questions--

27
00:01:37,473 --> 00:01:41,341
friendship, character,

28
00:01:41,411 --> 00:01:43,743
ethics.

29
00:01:46,883 --> 00:01:48,942
So, it's clear what I'm saying?

30
00:01:50,386 --> 00:01:53,253
As mud.

31
00:01:55,825 --> 00:01:59,825
It's gettin' so a businessman
can't expect no return
from a fixed fight.

32
00:02:01,631 --> 00:02:05,089
Now, if you can't trust a fix,
what can you trust?

33
00:02:05,168 --> 00:02:08,569
{i1}For a good return, you gotta
go bettin' on chance,{}

34
00:02:08,638 --> 00:02:10,868
{i1}and then you're
back with anarchy.{}

35
00:02:10,940 --> 00:02:12,874
{i1}Right back in the jungle.{}

36
00:02:12,942 --> 00:02:16,942
{i1}That's why ethics is important--
what separates us
from the animals,{}

37
00:02:18,081 --> 00:02:20,549
{i1}the beasts of burden,
the beasts of prey.{}

38
00:02:20,616 --> 00:02:22,584
Ethics.

39
00:02:22,652 --> 00:02:26,652
Where as, uh, Bernie Bernbaum
is a horse of a different color,

40
00:02:26,923 --> 00:02:30,654
ethics-wise, as in
he ain't got any.

41
00:02:30,727 --> 00:02:34,727
- You sure it's Bernie
selling you out?
- It ain't elves.

42
00:02:34,897 --> 00:02:38,765
- No one else knows about the fix?
- No one that ain't got ethics.

43
00:02:38,835 --> 00:02:41,861
{i1}What about the fighters
you pay to tank out?{}

44
00:02:41,938 --> 00:02:45,874
We only pick fighters
we know we can put
the fear of God in.

45
00:02:45,942 --> 00:02:48,240
Any other bookies know?
You play anyone else's book?

46
00:02:48,311 --> 00:02:51,542
I-I lay an occasional bet
with Mink Larouie.

47
00:02:51,614 --> 00:02:54,139
- But it ain't Mink.
I'll vouch for that.
{i1}-How do you know?{}

48
00:02:54,217 --> 00:02:57,482
It ain't Mink.
Mink is Eddie Dane's boy.

49
00:02:57,553 --> 00:03:01,387
Of course the Dane
always knows about the fix.

50
00:03:01,457 --> 00:03:03,584
And what the hell
is that supposed to mean?

51
00:03:03,659 --> 00:03:07,186
Let it drift. All it means is
a lot of people know.

52
00:03:07,263 --> 00:03:09,629
I guess you ain't
been listenin'.

53
00:03:09,699 --> 00:03:11,894
Sure, other people know.

54
00:03:11,968 --> 00:03:14,664
{i1}That's why we gotta go
to this question of character...{}

55
00:03:14,737 --> 00:03:18,434
to determine just who, exactly,
is chiselin' in on my fix.

56
00:03:18,508 --> 00:03:22,274
And that's how we know
that it's Bernie Bernbaum,
the {i1}shmatte{} kid--

57
00:03:22,345 --> 00:03:25,439
'cause ethically,
he's kinda shaky.

58
00:03:26,682 --> 00:03:30,682
- So you want to kill him.
- For starters.

59
00:03:45,168 --> 00:03:49,168
Sorry, Caspar.
Bernie pays for protection.

60
00:03:51,207 --> 00:03:54,404
Listen, Leo, I ain't
askin' you for permission.

61
00:03:54,477 --> 00:03:58,477
I'm tellin' you as a courtesy.
I need to do this thing,
so it's gonna get done.

62
00:03:58,714 --> 00:04:00,648
And I'm tellin' you, as
a courtesy, you'll have trouble.

63
00:04:00,716 --> 00:04:04,584
You came here to see if
I'd kick if you killed Bernie.
Well, there's your answer.

64
00:04:04,654 --> 00:04:08,317
I pay off to you every month
like a greengrocer

65
00:04:08,391 --> 00:04:10,382
a lot more than the {i1}shmatte,{}

66
00:04:10,460 --> 00:04:12,394
and I'm sick of gettin'
the high hat.

67
00:04:12,462 --> 00:04:15,488
{i1}You pay off for protection
just like everyone else.{i1}

68
00:04:15,565 --> 00:04:18,363
As far as I know, and
what I don't know in this town
ain't worth knowing,

69
00:04:18,434 --> 00:04:20,425
the cops haven't closed
any of your dives...

70
00:04:20,503 --> 00:04:22,994
and the D.A. hasn't touched
any of your rackets.

71
00:04:23,072 --> 00:04:25,597
{i1}You haven't bought any license
to kill bookies,{}

72
00:04:25,675 --> 00:04:27,666
{i1}and today I ain't sellin' any.{}

73
00:04:27,743 --> 00:04:30,644
So take your funky and dangle.

74
00:04:30,713 --> 00:04:34,713
You think I'm some guinea
fresh off the boat,
and you can kick me.

75
00:04:35,184 --> 00:04:39,184
But I'm too big for that now.
I'm sick of takin'
the strap from you, Leo.

76
00:04:39,322 --> 00:04:41,688
I'm sick of marching
into this goddamn office...

77
00:04:41,757 --> 00:04:43,782
to kiss your Irish ass,

78
00:04:43,860 --> 00:04:46,351
and I'm sick of the high hat!

79
00:05:02,979 --> 00:05:06,278
You's fancy pants, all of youse.

80
00:05:08,151 --> 00:05:10,619
Johnny?

81
00:05:10,686 --> 00:05:14,019
{i1}You're exactly as big
as I let you be and no bigger,{}

82
00:05:14,090 --> 00:05:16,388
and don't forget it, ever.

83
00:05:18,961 --> 00:05:20,895
That's right, Leo.

84
00:05:20,963 --> 00:05:23,056
You're the big shot
around here,

85
00:05:23,132 --> 00:05:26,795
and I'm just some schnook
likes to get slapped around.

86
00:05:31,974 --> 00:05:34,101
[ Chuckles ]

87
00:05:34,177 --> 00:05:37,146
Twist a pig's ear,
watch him squeal.

88
00:05:45,821 --> 00:05:49,382
- Bad play, Leo.
- Who got up the wrong side, huh?

89
00:05:49,458 --> 00:05:52,291
{i1}-Same side as always.{}
- That's what I mean.
Still owe money to--

90
00:05:52,361 --> 00:05:55,819
Who is your bookie, Lazarre?
I could put it right for you.

91
00:05:55,898 --> 00:05:58,924
- Thanks, Leo. I don't need it.
{i1}- In a pig's eye.{}

92
00:05:59,001 --> 00:06:00,935
You haven't played
a winner in six weeks.

93
00:06:01,003 --> 00:06:03,403
People will speak ill of me
if I let him break your legs.

94
00:06:03,472 --> 00:06:07,340
- People will say I had it coming.
{i1}-And they'll be right,
but that ain't the point.{}

95
00:06:07,410 --> 00:06:11,278
Call me a bighearted slob,
but I'm gonna square it
for you, yeah.

96
00:06:11,347 --> 00:06:14,805
I think I'll do that
this very same night.

97
00:06:14,884 --> 00:06:18,752
Lookin' at you mopin' around
takes away all my--

98
00:06:18,821 --> 00:06:21,415
What do you call it?
"Joy de veever"?

99
00:06:21,490 --> 00:06:24,584
{i1}-Joie de vivre.{}
- Well, if you're gonna
laugh at me, the hell with ya.

100
00:06:24,660 --> 00:06:27,288
The hell with you.

101
00:06:27,363 --> 00:06:29,763
I'll square myself with Lazarre,
if you don't mind.

102
00:06:29,832 --> 00:06:32,733
{i1}That's why God invented cards.{}

103
00:06:35,238 --> 00:06:38,071
- There is one thing
you can do for me.
{i1}- Name it.{}

104
00:06:38,140 --> 00:06:40,631
Think about what
protecting Bernie gets us.

105
00:06:40,710 --> 00:06:43,304
Think about what
offending Caspar loses us.

106
00:06:43,379 --> 00:06:45,745
Oh, come on, Tommy.
You know I don't like to think.

107
00:06:45,815 --> 00:06:47,874
Yeah.

108
00:06:47,875 --> 00:06:48,875
Well, think about
whether you should start.

109
00:08:36,461 --> 00:08:38,793
{i1}Wake up, Tommy.{}

110
00:08:38,864 --> 00:08:41,992
- I am awake.
- Your eyes are shut.

111
00:08:42,067 --> 00:08:44,331
Who you gonna believe?

112
00:08:47,139 --> 00:08:49,266
[ Groans ]

113
00:08:54,880 --> 00:08:57,508
- How'd I do?
- What do you think?

114
00:08:57,582 --> 00:09:00,415
You are a millionaire.
You gonna remember your friends?

115
00:09:03,755 --> 00:09:07,418
- Where's me hat?
- You bet it, mug.

116
00:09:07,492 --> 00:09:11,019
Good thing the game broke up
before you bet your trousers.

117
00:09:12,230 --> 00:09:15,495
- Who made off with me hat?

118
00:09:15,567 --> 00:09:18,365
Verna. Verna and Mink.

119
00:09:18,437 --> 00:09:20,837
{i1}- Who?{}
- Mink and Verna.

120
00:09:22,708 --> 00:09:25,677
[Vomiting]

121
00:09:28,580 --> 00:09:30,946
{i1}Is Thunderclap running tonight?{}

122
00:09:31,016 --> 00:09:34,247
Thunderclap?
Yeah.

123
00:09:34,319 --> 00:09:36,344
{i1}What's she leaving at?{}

124
00:09:36,421 --> 00:09:39,083
Three to one, more than likely.

125
00:09:39,157 --> 00:09:42,388
Lay off, Tom. You shouldn't go
deeper in the hole.

126
00:09:42,461 --> 00:09:44,986
Tell Lazarre...

127
00:09:45,063 --> 00:09:48,521
{i1}I want 500 on the nose.{}

128
00:09:48,600 --> 00:09:51,160
You would have it.

129
00:10:04,049 --> 00:10:06,745
I want me hat.

130
00:10:06,818 --> 00:10:10,618
Is that all you came for?

131
00:10:10,689 --> 00:10:13,021
Yeah. I want me hat.

132
00:10:13,091 --> 00:10:15,252
It's mine. I won it.

133
00:10:15,327 --> 00:10:18,091
- What are you gonna do with it?
- Drop dead.

134
00:10:26,538 --> 00:10:29,439
I need a drink.

135
00:10:29,508 --> 00:10:32,136
Why didn't you say so?

136
00:10:54,266 --> 00:10:55,790
[Knocking On Door]

137
00:10:58,303 --> 00:11:00,863
[Knocking Continues]

138
00:11:08,914 --> 00:11:11,382
[Knocking Continues]

139
00:11:28,600 --> 00:11:31,694
Hello, Tommy.
Sorry about the hour.

140
00:11:31,770 --> 00:11:35,604
- I'll live. What's the rumpus?
{i1}- Can I come in?{}

141
00:11:38,176 --> 00:11:40,701
Sure.

142
00:11:49,354 --> 00:11:52,551
- Drink?
- I wouldn't mind.

143
00:11:59,364 --> 00:12:01,525
I tried callin' earlier.

144
00:12:01,600 --> 00:12:04,228
I got home late.

145
00:12:09,441 --> 00:12:13,441
- Well, uh, I'm sorry about the hour.
{i1}- Uh-huh.{}

146
00:12:27,158 --> 00:12:30,753
- Not bad.
- Better than the paint
we sell at the club.

147
00:12:30,829 --> 00:12:33,457
That it is. That it is.

148
00:12:37,002 --> 00:12:39,232
- You thought about
cutting Bernie loose?
- Can't do it, Tommy.

149
00:12:39,304 --> 00:12:42,296
Can't do it.

150
00:12:42,374 --> 00:12:44,899
That's sort of why I'm, uh--

151
00:12:47,512 --> 00:12:50,538
Tommy, I don't know where Verna is.

152
00:12:50,615 --> 00:12:53,914
- Uh-huh.
- I know what youre thinkin',
what else is new?

153
00:12:53,985 --> 00:12:56,977
But the situation now--
I'm worried.

154
00:12:57,055 --> 00:13:00,491
Verna can take care of herself,
maybe better than you can.

155
00:13:00,558 --> 00:13:04,153
- What does that mean?
- Want another one?

156
00:13:04,229 --> 00:13:06,163
No.

157
00:13:06,231 --> 00:13:08,290
What does that mean?

158
00:13:08,366 --> 00:13:10,766
How far she got
her hooks into you?

159
00:13:10,835 --> 00:13:12,928
That's a hell of a question.

160
00:13:15,073 --> 00:13:17,337
It's a grift.

161
00:13:17,409 --> 00:13:21,072
If she didn't need you
to protect her brother
from Johnny Caspar,

162
00:13:21,146 --> 00:13:24,809
you think she'd still be going
on slow carriage rides with you
through the park?

163
00:13:24,883 --> 00:13:28,883
{i1}That's the deal, isnt it?
You keep Bernie under wraps
till Caspar cools down?{}

164
00:13:29,354 --> 00:13:33,222
Jesus, you're a prickly pear.
What's wrong with her wanting
her brother taken care of?

165
00:13:33,291 --> 00:13:35,225
{i1}Nothing. I don't blame her.{}

166
00:13:35,293 --> 00:13:37,625
She sees the angle,
which is you, she plays it.

167
00:13:37,696 --> 00:13:40,665
{i1}She's a grifter,
just like her brother.{}

168
00:13:40,732 --> 00:13:42,996
Probably had grifter parents
and grifter grandparents...

169
00:13:43,068 --> 00:13:46,162
and someday they're each
gonna spawn little grifter kids.

170
00:13:46,237 --> 00:13:49,468
Stop it, Tommy.
I don't like to hear my friends
run down, even by other friends.

171
00:13:49,541 --> 00:13:51,736
- Friendship's got
nothing to do with it.
{i1}- The hell you say.{}

172
00:13:51,810 --> 00:13:54,574
You'd do anything to help
your friends, like you'd do
anything to kick your enemies.

173
00:13:56,090 --> 00:13:58,024
{i1}- Wrong, Leo.
You do things for a reason.
- Okay, Tom.{}

174
00:13:58,092 --> 00:14:01,289
You know all the angles,
Christ, better than anybody.

175
00:14:03,264 --> 00:14:06,461
But may be you're wrong
about this. You don't know
what's in Verna's heart.

176
00:14:06,534 --> 00:14:09,401
Leo, if she's such an angel,

177
00:14:09,470 --> 00:14:11,734
why are you looking for her
at 4:00 in the morning?

178
00:14:14,108 --> 00:14:16,076
[ Sighs ]

179
00:14:16,144 --> 00:14:18,078
I put a tail on her this afternoon.

180
00:14:19,514 --> 00:14:23,514
- Uh-huh.
- I asked Rug Daniels
to follow her around,

181
00:14:24,218 --> 00:14:27,415
just, you know,
to keep her out of trouble.

182
00:14:27,488 --> 00:14:31,488
I was worried.
After that meeting with Caspar,
you can't be too careful.

183
00:14:31,693 --> 00:14:34,992
- So what did Rug say that has you
scurrying over here?
- That's just it.

184
00:14:35,063 --> 00:14:39,063
- Nothing. He's disappeared.
- So you lost your lady friend
and the tail you put on her?

185
00:14:40,802 --> 00:14:43,396
I guess it does sound
pretty sorry at that.

186
00:14:43,471 --> 00:14:46,929
Help me out, Tom.
I wouldn't know where
to start lookin'.

187
00:14:47,008 --> 00:14:49,568
You know Rug's crowd.
You know the people Verna runs with.

188
00:14:49,644 --> 00:14:53,273
It's just I'm worried now
with things the way they are
between me and Caspar.

189
00:14:53,348 --> 00:14:56,181
You shouldn't be confronting
Johnny Caspar. That's what
I've been trying to tell you.

190
00:14:56,250 --> 00:14:59,083
You can't trade
body blows with him.
He's gotten too strong.

191
00:14:59,153 --> 00:15:03,153
I reckon I can still trade body blows
with any man in this town.

192
00:15:07,295 --> 00:15:10,025
Except you, Tom.

193
00:15:10,098 --> 00:15:12,032
And Verna.

194
00:15:17,071 --> 00:15:20,404
[ Chuckles ]

195
00:15:22,010 --> 00:15:24,604
Okay. Give me the needle.

196
00:15:26,481 --> 00:15:29,609
I am a sap.
[ Grunts ]

197
00:15:29,684 --> 00:15:33,017
I deserve it.

198
00:15:33,087 --> 00:15:35,180
Thanks for the drink.

199
00:15:36,624 --> 00:15:38,990
Let me know
if you hear anything.

200
00:16:07,555 --> 00:16:11,116
- Who was that?
- Leo.

201
00:16:11,192 --> 00:16:13,422
He's lookin' for you.

202
00:16:13,494 --> 00:16:15,962
Did you tell him I was here?

203
00:16:16,030 --> 00:16:18,521
No.

204
00:16:20,968 --> 00:16:24,369
Did you put in a good word
for my brother?

205
00:16:24,439 --> 00:16:26,532
No.

206
00:16:26,607 --> 00:16:29,838
- You said you would.
- I said I'd think about it.

207
00:16:31,946 --> 00:16:34,107
What did you tell him?

208
00:16:37,151 --> 00:16:39,984
Did you see
Rug Daniels last night?

209
00:16:40,054 --> 00:16:42,420
No.

210
00:16:42,490 --> 00:16:44,583
What did you tell Leo?

211
00:16:44,659 --> 00:16:47,321
I told him you were a tramp
and he should dump you.

212
00:16:51,265 --> 00:16:54,098
You're a son of a bitch, Tom.

213
00:16:54,099 --> 00:16:55,099
[Man Whistling]

214
00:17:36,377 --> 00:17:38,538
[ Barking ]

215
00:17:43,885 --> 00:17:46,410
[Chattering, Indistinct]

216
00:18:00,268 --> 00:18:03,294
[Car Horns Sounding]

217
00:18:07,275 --> 00:18:09,402
- Hello, Tom.
What's the rumpus?
- Mink.

218
00:18:09,477 --> 00:18:11,570
- I see you got your hat back.
- Yeah, what of it?

219
00:18:11,646 --> 00:18:13,739
Not a thing. Look,
if it ain't my business,
I got not a thing to say.

220
00:18:13,815 --> 00:18:15,749
Listen, Bernie wants to see you.
It's important.

221
00:18:15,817 --> 00:18:17,751
Yeah, well, I'm right here.
I'm not made of glass.

222
00:18:17,819 --> 00:18:20,481
He's nervous walkin' around
in public. He's a right guy,
but he's very nervous.

223
00:18:20,555 --> 00:18:23,149
I mean, who wouldn't be?
In the spot he's in,
who wouldn't be?

224
00:18:23,224 --> 00:18:25,556
He asked me to ask you
to ask Leo to take care of him.

225
00:18:25,626 --> 00:18:27,651
Leo listens to you.
Not that Leo wouldn't help
a shmatte anyway.

226
00:18:27,728 --> 00:18:30,060
A guy like Bernie?
A straight shooter like him?

227
00:18:30,131 --> 00:18:32,929
- I don't get it, Mink.
- What's to get? It's as plain
as the nose on your face.

228
00:18:33,000 --> 00:18:35,332
- I thought you were
Eddie Dane's sycophant.
- Yeah, Tom, that's right,

229
00:18:35,403 --> 00:18:37,337
but a guy can have more
than one friend, can't he?

230
00:18:37,405 --> 00:18:40,533
Not that I want the Dane to know
about it, but the shmatte,
he's a right guy, Tommy.

231
00:18:40,608 --> 00:18:43,202
He's got a mixed reputation,
but for a sheeny, he's got
a lot of good qualities.

232
00:18:43,277 --> 00:18:46,542
- What's goin' on
between you and Bernie?
- Nothin', Tom.

233
00:18:46,614 --> 00:18:48,639
Were just...
friends, you know, amigos.

234
00:18:48,716 --> 00:18:51,082
You're a fickle boy, Mink.

235
00:18:51,152 --> 00:18:55,152
If Eddie Dane finds out
that you got another "amigo"--

236
00:18:55,523 --> 00:18:59,152
- Well, I don't peg him
for the understanding type.
- Find out?

237
00:18:59,227 --> 00:19:01,889
How's he gonna find out?
Damn it, you and me
ain't even been talkin'!

238
00:19:01,963 --> 00:19:04,431
Jesus, Tom! Damn it! Jesus!

239
00:19:04,498 --> 00:19:06,659
[Men Chuckling]

240
00:19:06,734 --> 00:19:09,259
[Leo]
Hello, Tommy.

241
00:19:09,337 --> 00:19:12,534
- You know O'Doole and the mayor?
-I oughta.

242
00:19:12,607 --> 00:19:15,269
Voted for him six times last May.

243
00:19:15,343 --> 00:19:17,402
And that ain't the record, either.

244
00:19:17,478 --> 00:19:19,412
- [ Laughs ]
- [ Laughs ]

245
00:19:19,480 --> 00:19:23,480
Oh, Verna turned up.
She's downstairs.

246
00:19:23,684 --> 00:19:27,017
- She say where she'd been?
- No. I didnt want to press her.

247
00:19:27,088 --> 00:19:31,088
- You hear about Rug?
- Yeah. R.I.P.

248
00:19:31,525 --> 00:19:34,517
They took his hair, Tommy.

249
00:19:34,595 --> 00:19:37,291
Jesus, that's strange.
Why would they do that?

250
00:19:37,365 --> 00:19:41,365
- Maybe it was injuns.
- Eye-ties, more like it.

251
00:19:44,038 --> 00:19:45,972
Giovanni Gasparo.

252
00:19:46,040 --> 00:19:48,907
So you figure Caspar bumped Rug.

253
00:19:48,976 --> 00:19:51,604
- Well, it's pretty obvious, ain't it?
- Yeah?

254
00:19:51,679 --> 00:19:55,679
- So what's the plan?
- Well, we'll jump on the guinea
hard with both feet.

255
00:19:56,751 --> 00:20:00,243
- Give him the low down, Dale.
- Yes. Well, um,

256
00:20:00,321 --> 00:20:03,051
Leo here just reminded us
that Mr. Caspar operates...

257
00:20:03,124 --> 00:20:05,149
several clubs in our city,

258
00:20:05,226 --> 00:20:09,219
wherein the patrons
imbibe of rum and play
at games of chance.

259
00:20:09,297 --> 00:20:11,458
And we're supposed to
stop the party.

260
00:20:11,532 --> 00:20:14,592
- They don't look
to happy about it, Leo.
- Oh, no, it ain't that, Tom.

261
00:20:14,669 --> 00:20:17,729
-Jesus, Tom, we do as we're told.
- Maybe they're right
not to like it.

262
00:20:17,805 --> 00:20:20,933
Stirring up this hornet's nest
won't be good for anyone,
and it'll mean killing.

263
00:20:21,008 --> 00:20:24,102
I'm not thrilled
about it either, but I can't
just lay down to Caspar.

264
00:20:24,178 --> 00:20:26,738
You could do worse.
You might not like it, but
giving up Bernie Bernbaum...

265
00:20:26,814 --> 00:20:28,782
is a pretty small price
to pay for peace.

266
00:20:28,849 --> 00:20:31,943
Business is business,
and a war is going to hurt everybody.

267
00:20:32,019 --> 00:20:34,351
Bernie plays with fire,
hes got to deal
with the consequences.

268
00:20:34,422 --> 00:20:36,413
even if that means
he gets bumped off.

269
00:20:36,490 --> 00:20:40,483
Sweet Jesus, Tom, that ain't
even the point anymore.
Caspar pooped Rug.

270
00:20:40,561 --> 00:20:43,394
The day I back down
from a fight, Caspar's
welcome to the rackets,

271
00:20:43,464 --> 00:20:45,523
this town and my place
at the table.

272
00:20:45,599 --> 00:20:47,692
- I didn't start this thing, but--
- You did start it.

273
00:20:47,768 --> 00:20:51,260
- You and Verna.
- We can dangle, Leo,
if youd prefer.

274
00:20:51,339 --> 00:20:53,364
Sit down, Dale!
We're all friends here.

275
00:20:53,441 --> 00:20:56,899
And Caspar hasn't
broken the rules, Bernie has,
and you, too, by helping him.

276
00:20:56,978 --> 00:20:59,139
And if that isn't enough,
consider that if you
make this a war,

277
00:20:59,213 --> 00:21:01,374
you have more to lose than Caspar.

278
00:21:01,449 --> 00:21:05,449
Okay, but more to beat him with.
Jesus, Tom, the two of us
have faced worse odds.

279
00:21:05,546 --> 00:21:08,546
Never without reason.
It helps to have one.

280
00:21:14,563 --> 00:21:17,498
[ Scoffs ]
Well, it's your call.

281
00:21:19,134 --> 00:21:21,432
My opinion used to count
for something around here.

282
00:21:21,503 --> 00:21:23,630
But it's always yours
to take or leave.

283
00:21:23,705 --> 00:21:25,639
Come on, Tommy.
It's not like that.

284
00:21:27,142 --> 00:21:30,168
Goddamn it!

285
00:21:32,480 --> 00:21:35,244
Goddamn kid's just like a twist.

286
00:21:35,317 --> 00:21:37,808
Get me a stiff one.

287
00:21:39,220 --> 00:21:41,518
No small talk, huh?

288
00:21:43,758 --> 00:21:47,023
- They shoot your horse?
- If there's any justice.

289
00:21:48,463 --> 00:21:50,954
- Verna around?
- She stepped into
the ladies' room.

290
00:21:51,032 --> 00:21:54,297
- You got Lazarre's 500?
- You'll have to carry me
for a few days.

291
00:21:54,369 --> 00:21:57,429
He ain't gonna like that.
Couldn't you get it from Leo?

292
00:21:57,505 --> 00:22:00,804
It's not Leo's debt.
I'll pay me own way.

293
00:22:00,875 --> 00:22:02,775
I admire a man of principle.

294
00:22:04,546 --> 00:22:07,515
Does this go on the tab?

295
00:22:07,582 --> 00:22:10,278
-[Women Gasping]
- Close your eyes, ladies.
I'm coming through.

296
00:22:14,623 --> 00:22:18,150
- Who's the war paint for?
- Go home and dry out.

297
00:22:19,327 --> 00:22:21,352
You don't need it for Leo,
believe me.

298
00:22:21,429 --> 00:22:23,897
He already thinks you're
the original Miss Jesus.

299
00:22:23,965 --> 00:22:26,092
- What the hell's
the matter with you?
- What's the matter with you?

300
00:22:26,167 --> 00:22:29,728
- Afraid people might get
the right idea?
- Leo's got the right idea.

301
00:22:29,804 --> 00:22:32,466
I like him.
He's honest and he's got a heart.

302
00:22:32,540 --> 00:22:34,804
Then it's true what they say--
opposites attract.

303
00:22:34,876 --> 00:22:38,368
- Do me a favor.
Mind your own business.
- This is my business.

304
00:22:38,446 --> 00:22:41,313
Intimidating helpless women
is part of what I do.

305
00:22:41,383 --> 00:22:43,544
- Then find one
and intimidate her.
-Leo's upstairs...

306
00:22:43,618 --> 00:22:45,984
getting ready to shoot himself
in the foot on your account.

307
00:22:46,054 --> 00:22:47,988
-I don't know
what youre talkin' about.
- He's gonna go to the mat...

308
00:22:48,056 --> 00:22:49,990
for your brother,
and it's gonna hurt him.

309
00:22:50,058 --> 00:22:52,253
I don't know Leo's business,
but he's a big boy.

310
00:22:52,327 --> 00:22:54,352
- He used to be.
- Look, what do you want, Tom?

311
00:22:54,429 --> 00:22:57,262
You want me to pretend
I don't care what happens to Bernie?

312
00:22:57,332 --> 00:23:00,062
Well, I do.
He's my brother. I don't
want to see him get hurt.

313
00:23:00,135 --> 00:23:04,135
If Leo wants to help out,
Ill step out with him,
show him a good time in return.

314
00:23:04,639 --> 00:23:08,006
- There's no harm in that.
- There's a name for that kind
of business arrangement.

315
00:23:08,076 --> 00:23:11,603
Look, I'll do what I have to do
to protect Bernie.

316
00:23:11,680 --> 00:23:14,012
There's no reason for you
to try and queer that.

317
00:23:14,082 --> 00:23:16,710
Regardless of what
you think about me,
Bernie's a decent guy.

318
00:23:16,785 --> 00:23:20,448
- A straight shooter, huh?
A square "G."
- Yeah.

319
00:23:20,522 --> 00:23:24,522
Sneer at him like everyone else,
just because he's different.

320
00:23:24,859 --> 00:23:27,521
People think he's a degenerate.
People think he's scum.

321
00:23:27,595 --> 00:23:31,190
- Well, he's not.
-Poor misunderstood Bernie.

322
00:23:31,266 --> 00:23:33,700
What is this about, Tom?

323
00:23:33,768 --> 00:23:37,204
You want me to stop seeing Leo?
Why don't you just say so?

324
00:23:39,040 --> 00:23:42,476
I want you to quit
spinning Leo in circles
and pointing him where to go.

325
00:23:42,544 --> 00:23:45,012
- I forgot. That's your job.
- I'll do what I have to do
to protect Leo.

326
00:23:45,080 --> 00:23:48,481
I'm asking you politely.
Leave him alone.
I don't have to ask.

327
00:23:48,550 --> 00:23:51,747
If I told him about our little
dance last night, your pool
would pretty soon dry up.

328
00:23:51,820 --> 00:23:53,879
So would yours.
I don't like being threatened.

329
00:23:53,955 --> 00:23:57,955
I don't like being taken for
a sucker. That might work with
Leo, but it don't work with me.

330
00:23:58,226 --> 00:24:01,423
Do you think last night
was just more campaigning
for my brother?

331
00:24:01,496 --> 00:24:03,396
I can see the angles.

332
00:24:03,465 --> 00:24:05,558
You know, if there was a market
for little old ladies,

333
00:24:05,633 --> 00:24:07,624
you'd have Grandma Bernbaum
first in line.

334
00:24:07,702 --> 00:24:10,432
- You're a pathetic rum head.
- And I love you, angel.

335
00:24:26,921 --> 00:24:29,947
I suppose you think
you raised hell.

336
00:24:33,995 --> 00:24:37,590
Sister, when I've raised hell,
you'll know it.

337
00:24:40,502 --> 00:24:43,437
[ Phone Ringing ]

338
00:24:43,505 --> 00:24:45,769
[Door Opening]

339
00:25:14,369 --> 00:25:17,805
- Yeah.
- [ Man ] Lazarre wants
his money. He wants it now.

340
00:25:17,872 --> 00:25:20,363
- I need a couple of days.
- Yeah? How come is that?

341
00:25:20,441 --> 00:25:24,441
- Because I don't have it.
- All right, welsher, how do I
know you ain't got it?

342
00:25:24,746 --> 00:25:28,746
- Because I say so.
- That ain't gonna be good enough.

343
00:25:28,883 --> 00:25:32,478
- What would be good enough?
- Lazarre ain't gonna
like it one bit.

344
00:25:32,554 --> 00:25:35,489
Tell Lazarre if hes not happy,
he can send someone over
to break my legs.

345
00:25:35,557 --> 00:25:38,549
I won't squawk.

346
00:25:40,195 --> 00:25:42,891
- Hello, Bernie.
- Hello, Tom.

347
00:25:42,964 --> 00:25:46,593
- What's the rumpus?
-Come on in.
Make your self at home.

348
00:25:46,668 --> 00:25:49,228
Yeah, you weren't here,
so I thought I'd do that.

349
00:25:49,304 --> 00:25:51,602
I didn't want to answer
the phone, though. I figured...

350
00:25:51,673 --> 00:25:53,607
it wasn't for me.

351
00:25:55,410 --> 00:25:58,208
[ Chuckles ]
I get it. Get to the point, huh?

352
00:25:58,279 --> 00:26:01,112
Okay. The point is,
I'm a good guy.

353
00:26:01,182 --> 00:26:03,116
I've heard that
from a lot of people today.

354
00:26:03,184 --> 00:26:05,084
Good guy, lots of friends.
That's the way it works.

355
00:26:05,153 --> 00:26:09,153
Maybe if you appreciated me
a little more, you wouldn't
be making waves with Leo.

356
00:26:09,891 --> 00:26:12,689
It's a bad time to be
doing that. Right now,
we're both in a jam.

357
00:26:12,760 --> 00:26:16,423
I hear youre on a bad streak.
Short of funds.

358
00:26:16,497 --> 00:26:19,796
Well, I got that crazy dago
mad at me.

359
00:26:19,868 --> 00:26:21,836
Don't ask me why.
I'm just a small-timer...

360
00:26:21,903 --> 00:26:24,201
trying to get by
like everyone else.

361
00:26:24,272 --> 00:26:27,264
I need help from my friends
like Leo and you.

362
00:26:27,342 --> 00:26:29,435
Leo gets your sister.
What are you sellin' me?

363
00:26:29,510 --> 00:26:31,910
Come on, Tom.
It's not like that at all.
It wasn't my idea.

364
00:26:31,980 --> 00:26:34,073
She'll sleep with anyone.
You know that.

365
00:26:34,148 --> 00:26:37,811
She even tried to teach me
a thing or two about bed artistry.

366
00:26:37,886 --> 00:26:40,719
Can you believe that?
[ Chuckles ]

367
00:26:40,788 --> 00:26:43,052
My own sister.
[ Chuckles ]

368
00:26:43,124 --> 00:26:47,124
Some crackpot idea about
saving me from my friends.

369
00:26:48,329 --> 00:26:50,490
She's a sick twist, all right.

370
00:26:50,565 --> 00:26:54,365
- She speaks highly of you.
- Yeah, well, you stick
by your family.

371
00:26:54,435 --> 00:26:56,995
The point is, I can help you
with your debts if that
would make us friends.

372
00:26:57,071 --> 00:27:00,472
My motto is,
A guy can't have too many.

373
00:27:00,541 --> 00:27:03,772
Big payday Saturday, Tom.
You could be in on it.

374
00:27:03,845 --> 00:27:06,143
Another fix? Which fight?

375
00:27:06,214 --> 00:27:10,214
That's confidential
at the moment. But it
doesn't have to stay that way.

376
00:27:10,351 --> 00:27:12,649
How come you know
so much about it?

377
00:27:12,720 --> 00:27:14,847
Caspar isn't laying
any more bets with you.

378
00:27:19,894 --> 00:27:22,761
You really must have Mink
jumping through hoops.

379
00:27:22,830 --> 00:27:26,163
Like I say, you can't
have too many.

380
00:27:26,234 --> 00:27:28,668
[ Exhales Deeply]

381
00:27:30,471 --> 00:27:34,464
- We got a deal?
- I'll think about it.

382
00:27:36,945 --> 00:27:39,277
I wouldn't want it any other way.

383
00:27:42,216 --> 00:27:44,776
Hey, Adolph.

384
00:27:46,721 --> 00:27:49,690
- My credit still
good with you?
- Mmm.

385
00:27:49,757 --> 00:27:52,453
Give me a hundred across on Tailor Made
in the third tonight.

386
00:27:52,527 --> 00:27:55,860
- Lazarre won't like it.
- Try 50 across.

387
00:27:55,930 --> 00:27:58,364
I'll try.
It's another 1 50 you'll owe him.

388
00:27:58,433 --> 00:28:01,891
- Only if I lose, Adolph.
- Tommy, the way youre goin'--

389
00:28:01,970 --> 00:28:05,531
- Hey, horses got knees?
- I don't know. Fetlocks.

390
00:28:05,606 --> 00:28:09,565
Well, if I was a horse,
I'd be down on my fetlocks
praying you don't bet on me.

391
00:28:09,644 --> 00:28:12,010
- Drift, small guy.
- Drop dead, ape.

392
00:28:12,080 --> 00:28:14,378
Come on, Tom.
Boss wants to see ya.

393
00:28:14,449 --> 00:28:16,849
He didn't have time
to engrave nothin' formal.

394
00:28:17,952 --> 00:28:21,513
[ Chattering In Italian ]

395
00:28:37,701 --> 00:28:41,701
What you mean, he's eatin' too much?
What's the goddamn doctor know?

396
00:28:43,273 --> 00:28:46,037
- What you eat for lunch?
- A hot dog.

397
00:28:46,110 --> 00:28:49,773
-Just a hot dog?
- A hot dog and mustard.

398
00:28:49,847 --> 00:28:53,847
A hot dog and mustard.
[ Laughs ]

399
00:28:54,485 --> 00:28:57,716
A hot dog and mustard!

400
00:28:59,423 --> 00:29:03,423
You hear that, Dane?
My kid is as smart as a whip.

401
00:29:03,560 --> 00:29:06,324
Even Uncle Eddie
thinks that's funny.

402
00:29:06,397 --> 00:29:09,298
Okay.

403
00:29:10,467 --> 00:29:13,994
Go ahead. Which hand
is the penny in?

404
00:29:15,272 --> 00:29:17,866
Choose again.

405
00:29:21,879 --> 00:29:25,076
Okay. Here you go.
Take the penny.
Shiny new penny.

406
00:29:25,149 --> 00:29:28,915
Take the kid,
wait in the car.
Give him a penny, boys!

407
00:29:30,821 --> 00:29:34,723
- I ain't got a penny, boss.
- That's a penny you owe him.

408
00:29:34,792 --> 00:29:38,319
Hello, Tom. What's the rumpus?
You like kids?

409
00:29:38,395 --> 00:29:41,660
- No.
- Have a seat. Go ahead.

410
00:29:43,167 --> 00:29:45,101
Well, you're missin' out
on a complete life.

411
00:29:45,169 --> 00:29:47,660
I know, kids, big deal.

412
00:29:47,738 --> 00:29:50,673
Still, I'm telling you.

413
00:29:50,741 --> 00:29:54,302
Anyways, thanks for comin' by.

414
00:29:55,813 --> 00:29:58,407
I just wrote this check out
to your bookmaker Lazarre.

415
00:29:58,482 --> 00:30:01,280
It's for an even 1 ,500,
which is more than I hear
you owe him,

416
00:30:01,351 --> 00:30:04,684
but I figured you could always
use some money on the cuff,
a high roller such as yourself.

417
00:30:04,755 --> 00:30:07,849
- What do you say?
- Thanks.

418
00:30:09,927 --> 00:30:12,293
Always they apper, huh?
[ Chuckles ]

419
00:30:12,362 --> 00:30:16,362
Well, you're welcome.
You wanna know why I'm puttin'
you square with Lazarre?

420
00:30:16,800 --> 00:30:20,133
- Not particularly.
- I want everybody to be friends.

421
00:30:20,204 --> 00:30:22,570
I do this, you're friends
with Lazarre,

422
00:30:22,639 --> 00:30:25,301
he's friends with you,
you're friends with me.

423
00:30:25,375 --> 00:30:29,375
All you gotta do
to show youre a friend
is give me Bernie Bernbaum.

424
00:30:29,880 --> 00:30:33,316
You know it's
the right thing anyway.
The shmatte steals from me.

425
00:30:33,383 --> 00:30:37,383
I can't have Leo giving him
a shiny new penny.

426
00:30:37,488 --> 00:30:39,649
So the deal is,
I give you Bernie,

427
00:30:39,723 --> 00:30:42,248
smooth it over with Leo
and you bail me out with Lazarre.

428
00:30:42,326 --> 00:30:44,453
Yeah. Then were all
friends again.
[Chuckles]

429
00:30:44,528 --> 00:30:47,258
You, me, Leo, the Dane.

430
00:30:47,331 --> 00:30:50,960
- We can maybe
have tea sometime.
- [Caspar]Come on, Eddie.

431
00:30:51,034 --> 00:30:54,003
Friends is a mental state.

432
00:30:54,071 --> 00:30:57,768
- What do you say, kid?
- I'll think about it.

433
00:30:57,841 --> 00:31:00,503
You'll think about it.
[ Chuckles ]

434
00:31:00,577 --> 00:31:03,569
You hear that, Dane?
The kid's a thinker.
That's terrific.

435
00:31:03,647 --> 00:31:07,515
- Does he want
a pillow for his head?
- Okay, kid. Think about it.

436
00:31:07,584 --> 00:31:11,384
It's a mental state.
If it'll help you think,

437
00:31:11,455 --> 00:31:14,015
you should know that if
you don't do this thing,

438
00:31:14,091 --> 00:31:16,651
you're not gonna be
in any shape to walk out of here.

439
00:31:18,462 --> 00:31:22,023
Would that be physically,
or just a mental state?

440
00:31:29,006 --> 00:31:32,373
That ain't friendly, kid.
I make you a nice offer,

441
00:31:32,442 --> 00:31:34,967
you give me the high hat.

442
00:32:14,985 --> 00:32:18,079
Hold it.

443
00:32:30,634 --> 00:32:33,865
Jesus, Tom.

444
00:33:14,478 --> 00:33:16,639
Just in the nick of time, huh?

445
00:33:20,550 --> 00:33:24,384
Well, no harm done.
Unless your friend broke his foot.

446
00:33:24,454 --> 00:33:27,821
- Where am I?
- Where are you? Johnny
Caspar's pleasure dome.

447
00:33:27,891 --> 00:33:30,826
Same as when you left us
about ten seconds ago.

448
00:33:30,894 --> 00:33:33,260
Hello, Tom. How are ya?

449
00:33:33,330 --> 00:33:35,525
Care to scrape a knuckle
on your playmate here?

450
00:33:35,599 --> 00:33:38,397
- No. Thanks though, Andy.
- Well, if you
change your mind,

451
00:33:38,468 --> 00:33:41,801
we'll be interrogating
for a while.

452
00:33:41,872 --> 00:33:45,239
- What was that party
about, anyway?
- We do this every weekend.

453
00:33:45,308 --> 00:33:47,902
Jesus, what is the matter
with you people?

454
00:33:47,978 --> 00:33:50,776
Well, they said make it hurt,
so we make it hurt.

455
00:33:57,154 --> 00:33:59,088
Drink, O'Doole?

456
00:33:59,156 --> 00:34:01,386
I'm on duty.

457
00:34:01,458 --> 00:34:04,256
To Volstead.

458
00:34:05,696 --> 00:34:07,823
- [Bottle Breaks]
- Any news about Rug?

459
00:34:07,898 --> 00:34:10,389
Still dead, far as I know.

460
00:34:10,467 --> 00:34:13,197
- Get a slug out of him?
- Yeah, .22.

461
00:34:13,270 --> 00:34:16,000
Listen, Tom, I'm just
the chief around here,

462
00:34:16,073 --> 00:34:18,132
so don't bother tellin' me
if you don't happen to
feel like it,

463
00:34:18,208 --> 00:34:20,142
but what the hell is Leo doin'?

464
00:34:20,210 --> 00:34:24,210
Make him listen to you, Tom.
It ain't right, all this fuss
over one sheeny.

465
00:34:24,748 --> 00:34:27,683
Let Caspar have Bernie.
What's one Hebrew more or less?

466
00:34:27,751 --> 00:34:29,685
We're burnin'
our meal ticket here.

467
00:34:29,753 --> 00:34:31,983
Leo will do what suits him,
and you'll do what he tells you.

468
00:34:32,055 --> 00:34:33,989
Last I heard, Leo was still
running this town.

469
00:34:34,057 --> 00:34:36,685
Yeah, well, he won't be
for long if this keeps up.

470
00:34:36,760 --> 00:34:39,524
It's no good for anyone.
You said as much yourself.

471
00:34:39,596 --> 00:34:43,596
First off, O'Doole, I can
say what I please to Leo
and about him.

472
00:34:43,867 --> 00:34:45,858
You cant.

473
00:34:45,936 --> 00:34:49,531
Second, once Leo decides,
that's that.

474
00:34:49,606 --> 00:34:52,040
If that sticks going down,
there are plenty
of coppers I know...

475
00:34:52,109 --> 00:34:54,976
who wouldn't mind
bein' chief and could
swallow it clean.

476
00:34:55,045 --> 00:34:59,045
Jesus, Tom,
I was just speculatin'
about a hypothesis.

477
00:34:59,216 --> 00:35:01,275
I know I don't
know nothin'.

478
00:35:01,351 --> 00:35:03,717
Its just a--
just a damn mess, is all.

479
00:35:03,787 --> 00:35:05,721
[Machine Gun Fire]

480
00:35:05,789 --> 00:35:09,020
[ Shouting, Indistinct ]

481
00:35:21,438 --> 00:35:22,905
[Door Closes]

482
00:35:27,725 --> 00:35:29,659
Hello, Officer. Id like to
report an intruder...

483
00:35:29,727 --> 00:35:32,787
at 346 West Lewis--

484
00:35:32,863 --> 00:35:36,458
Who's this?
Hello, Shad. Tom Reagan here.

485
00:35:36,534 --> 00:35:39,332
- You need the booze?
-[Tom]No, we won't be
needing any today.

486
00:35:39,403 --> 00:35:42,201
- False alarm, huh?
- Yeah. My mother.
She didn't recognize me.

487
00:35:42,273 --> 00:35:44,605
Let me talk to Mulveany.
Miss me?

488
00:35:44,675 --> 00:35:47,143
Drop dead.

489
00:35:47,211 --> 00:35:49,270
- Mulveany here.
- Sean?

490
00:35:49,346 --> 00:35:51,280
Tell O'Doole to get a car
over to Leo's tonight.

491
00:35:51,348 --> 00:35:54,317
If were banging away
at Caspar, we oughta be ready
for him to bang back.

492
00:35:54,385 --> 00:35:56,649
-[Hangs Up Phone]
- What do you want?

493
00:35:56,720 --> 00:36:00,486
I was in the neighborhood,
feeling a bit daffy,

494
00:36:00,558 --> 00:36:03,527
so I thought I'd drop in
for an aperitif.

495
00:36:05,262 --> 00:36:08,197
- Rug Daniels is dead.
- Gee, that's tough.

496
00:36:08,265 --> 00:36:10,460
Don't get hysterical.

497
00:36:10,534 --> 00:36:14,129
I've had enough excitement
for one night without a dame
going all weepy on me.

498
00:36:14,205 --> 00:36:16,332
- I barely knew the gentleman.
-Rug?

499
00:36:16,407 --> 00:36:20,407
A bit of a shakedown artist,
not above the occasional grift.

500
00:36:20,844 --> 00:36:24,644
Bet youd understand that.
All in all, not a bad guy,

501
00:36:24,715 --> 00:36:28,116
if looks, brains
and personality don't count.

502
00:36:28,185 --> 00:36:30,881
- You better hope they don't.
- Yeah, well--

503
00:36:30,955 --> 00:36:33,549
We're none of us the saint
I hear your brother is.

504
00:36:33,624 --> 00:36:35,819
- Who killed him?
- Leo thinks Caspar did.

505
00:36:35,893 --> 00:36:37,861
- But you know better.
- I do now.

506
00:36:37,928 --> 00:36:41,193
You see, Caspar just tried
to buy me into fixing
his tiff with Leo,

507
00:36:41,265 --> 00:36:44,029
which he'd hardly do
if he was waging war.

508
00:36:44,101 --> 00:36:48,101
So I figure you killed him, angel.
You or St. Bernard.

509
00:36:48,239 --> 00:36:52,039
Why would I or my brother
kill Rug Daniels or anybody else?

510
00:36:52,109 --> 00:36:56,109
Rug was following you.
He knew about you and me,

511
00:36:56,247 --> 00:36:58,875
and that wouldn't help
your play with Leo, would it?

512
00:36:58,949 --> 00:37:01,042
You think I murdered someone?

513
00:37:01,118 --> 00:37:04,212
Come on, Tom.
You know me a little.

514
00:37:04,288 --> 00:37:06,813
Nobody knows anybody.
Not that well.

515
00:37:06,890 --> 00:37:09,085
You know, or you
wouldn't be here.

516
00:37:09,159 --> 00:37:12,526
Not at all, sugar.
I came to hear your side of the story.

517
00:37:12,596 --> 00:37:16,596
How horrible Rug was,
how he goaded you into it,
how he tried to shake you down.

518
00:37:17,301 --> 00:37:19,394
- That's not why
you came either.
- Tell me why I came.

519
00:37:19,470 --> 00:37:22,598
- The oldest reason there is.
- There are friendlier
places to drink.

520
00:37:22,673 --> 00:37:24,607
- Why can't you admit it?
- Admit what?

521
00:37:24,675 --> 00:37:28,008
That you don't like
me seeing Leo
'cause you're jealous.

522
00:37:28,078 --> 00:37:30,376
Admit that you've
got a heart,

523
00:37:30,447 --> 00:37:32,915
even though it may be
small and feeble...

524
00:37:32,983 --> 00:37:35,178
and you can't remember
the last time you used it.

525
00:37:35,252 --> 00:37:38,415
If Id known we were gonna
cast our feelings into words,

526
00:37:38,489 --> 00:37:41,117
I'd have memorized
the Song of Solomon.

527
00:37:43,127 --> 00:37:46,358
Maybe that's why
I like you, Tom.

528
00:37:46,430 --> 00:37:49,228
I never knew anybody
that made being
a son of a bitch...

529
00:37:49,300 --> 00:37:51,996
such a point of pride.

530
00:37:52,069 --> 00:37:55,061
Though one day youll
pay the price for it.

531
00:37:56,407 --> 00:38:00,275
Okay, Verna.
But until then, let's get stinko.

532
00:38:00,344 --> 00:38:02,904
Let's do something else first.

533
00:38:07,618 --> 00:38:10,018
[Tom]
Yeah. Let's do plenty.

534
00:38:24,468 --> 00:38:26,629
[Clattering Sound]

535
